Br. Bob tells students how to deal with bullies

Following a column I wrote in
the fall on assertiveness, a stu-
dent wrote saying that the arti-
cle was helpful but asked ifl
had any suggestions for dealing
with parents, bosses or friends
who are too aggressive and try
to get their way through bully-
ing tactics.

Psychologists who have stud-
ied this problem over the years
generally conclude that bullies
are often anxious people.
Whenever they face a problem
involving other people they
have learned that they can
reduce their anxiety and often

get what they want by utilizing

an intimidating style.

The problem is that if you
give in to this kind of behavior
you reinforce it, and if you get
aggressive in return you get
caught in a power struggle that
is not helpful to either party.
Usually the best approach is to

try and understand what is caus-
ing the anxiety, confront the
behavior in a calm and reason-

Coping on
Campus
With Dr.

Robert

Gallagher

able way and attempt to negoti-
ate a solution that is beneficial
to both parties.

For instance, a student may
report to a parent that they are
failing a class and may not be
able to pass it. The parent goes
“ballistic” and demands that the
student avoid all social activi-
ties, break off a dating relation-
ship or follow some other

course of action that has little
objective merit.

It’s not hard in this instance to
figure out the source of the anx-
iety. The student can maintain
control in such a situation by
remaining calm in the face of
the onslaught and by not coun-
terattacking or caving in. Words
to the parent that might help
are, “I know that you are angry
at me for not doing better and
perhaps even a little scared for
me, but I’m scared also and
could use your support.” If the
bullying continues, stay cool
and suggest that perhaps it
would be better to talk about
this later when you both have
had more time to think about it.

Strategies for coping with bul-
lying behavior can be modiﬁed
to suit the different tempera-
ments of both parent and stu-
dent, but some approximation
of this approach, consistently

applied, can work wonders not
only with anxiously aggressive
parents, but with aggressive
friends as well.

This advice, of course, doesn’t
cover all aggressive encounters.
Beating a hasty retreat, for
instance, may be the best
course of action if there is phys-
ical danger. When verbally
attacked, however, you can
often keep control of the situa-
tion in two Ways. The first is by
stepping back from the emotion
of the moment to analyze what
is stimulating the anxiety in the
aggressor. The second is by
calmly and reasonably con-
fronting the person in a way
that demonstrates that you are
open to negotiating a solution
to the problem but that you will
not be bullied. This may not
work every time but it’s a plan
that can be effective in many sit-
uations of this kind.

