Lesbian Alliance.

The advertisement mentioned women
being used by the media to sell various
products and referred to theLambda Chi
Alpha fraternity’s rush poster as an exam-
ple.

Wording in the advertisement said that
Lambda Chi Alpha brought sexual harass-

ment onto Pitt’s campus by using scantily-
clothed women in their rush poster.

The closing phrase, “Get Angry! Get
Active!” struck a nerve with Pitt student
Ellie Miller.

“I found the advertisement to be very
threatening,” said Miller. “I don’t feel as a
woman that I need to be angry and that’s
what the ad was saying.”

CWO co-President Shira Hassan said the
advertisement “was meant to approach
some of the attitudes [women] have been
faced with on campus.”

Also in opposition to the advertisement’s
wording was Lori Goldstein. “I agree with
the issue,” said Goldstein. “I don’t believe

in the way it was stated.” _

Referring to a phrase in the advertise-
ment that stated no punishment was hand-
ed down to Lambda Chi Alpha for breaking
a rush code, Miller said the rush posters
had been taken down, that the fraternity
had apologized and editorials had been
written addressing the incident.

Hassan said, “We didn’t want to address
this fraternity, we wanted to address the
women angered by the [rush] poster.”

She said despite the complaints received
at the meeting, all other reactions she has
received have been very positive.

